---
import Atlas from '@/layouts/Atlas.astro';
import { getInventory, getAllPackages } from '@/lib/atlas';

const inv = await getInventory();
const pkgs = await getAllPackages();
const ch = inv.chapters.find(c => c.id === '06')!;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const sdkCore = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'sdk-core')!;
const webSdk  = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'web-sdk')!;
const nodeSdk = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'node-sdk')!;
const services = pkgs.find(p => p.id === 'sdk-services')!;
---
<Atlas chapter="06" title={ch.title} crumb={`06 · ${ch.title}`}>
  <article class="prose" style="padding: 56px 64px; max-width: 1100px;">
    <div class="label">chapter 06 · {ch.read} · voice: {ch.voice}</div>
    <h1 style="margin-top: 14px;">sharing — <span class="squig">portable bundles</span></h1>

    <p>
      Imagine you've authored a delegation chain (chapter
      <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/05/`}>05</a>): wallet to app,
      app to recipient, scope narrowed at every step. Now you want to
      hand it off — drop it in a chat, paste it into a URL, mail it.
      The recipient should be able to act on it without setting up a
      session of their own first. That's a <strong>share</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      A v2 share is a single self-contained artifact: a freshly minted
      ephemeral keypair, a delegation that authorizes that key, and the
      host the data lives at — all encoded into one <code>tc1:</code>-prefixed
      base64 string. Drop it into a URL, paste it into a chat, ship it
      over a postcard. <code>SharingService</code> in
      <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/pkg/sdk-core/`}>{sdkCore.npm}</a>
      builds them; <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/pkg/web-sdk/`}>{webSdk.npm}</a>
      and <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/pkg/node-sdk/`}>{nodeSdk.npm}</a>
      expose the public APIs.
    </p>

    <h2>tour — what's inside the link</h2>

    <div class="mermaid-wrap" style="margin: 24px 0; padding: 24px 24px 28px; position: relative;">
      <span class="cap">share-bundle.svg</span>

      <div class="mono" style="font-size: 12px; color: var(--ink-3); margin-bottom: 12px;">tc1:&lt;base64url&gt; …</div>

      <div class="col gap-12">
        <div class="card" style="padding: 12px 14px;">
          <div class="label">key</div>
          <div class="mono" style="font-size: 12px; margin-top: 4px;">jwk · ed25519 · { '{ kty, crv, x, d }' }</div>
          <div style="font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink-2); margin-top: 6px;">
            ephemeral. minted just for this share. <code>d</code> (the
            secret half) is in the bundle — that's the whole point.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card" style="padding: 12px 14px;">
          <div class="label">delegation</div>
          <div class="mono" style="font-size: 12px; margin-top: 4px;">cid · authHeader · expiry · isRevoked</div>
          <div style="font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink-2); margin-top: 6px;">
            already signed. authorizes the key above to invoke a
            specific service / space / path with a specific action set.
            stored content-addressed by CID.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card" style="padding: 12px 14px;">
          <div class="label">target</div>
          <div class="mono" style="font-size: 12px; margin-top: 4px;">spaceId · path · host · keyDid</div>
          <div style="font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink-2); margin-top: 6px;">
            where to point the request and which space / prefix to scope it to.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout" style="bottom: 18px; right: 24px; transform: rotate(-2deg); max-width: 200px;">
        no node lookup needed.<br/>everything to invoke is in the bundle.
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>generate — the issuer side</h2>

    <p>
      The author calls <code>SharingService.generate({ '{ path, actions, expiry }' })</code>.
      Internally, the service:
    </p>

    <ol style="font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; padding-left: 24px;">
      <li>mints a new <strong>share key</strong> (Ed25519, via the WASM seam).</li>
      <li>signs a delegation from the current session key (or, when the share outlives the session, directly from the wallet via <code>onRootDelegationNeeded</code>) to the share key.</li>
      <li>asks the node to register the delegation so it survives beyond the issuer's process.</li>
      <li>encodes <code>{ '{ key, delegation, host, spaceId, path, keyDid }' }</code> as JSON, base64-urls it, and prepends <code>tc1:</code>.</li>
      <li>returns a <code>ShareLink</code> with both the raw token and a fully composed URL.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      The default expiry is 24 h; the default scope on read-only shares
      is <code>tinycloud.kv/get</code> + <code>tinycloud.kv/metadata</code>.
      Both are overridable.
    </p>

    <h2>receive — the recipient side</h2>

    <p>
      Two flavors. If the recipient is already a logged-in TinyCloud
      user, <code>SharingService.receive(link)</code> ingests the
      delegation into the user's <code>CapabilityKeyRegistry</code> at
      priority 2 (below their own session key) and returns a pre-configured
      KV service the caller can hit immediately. The ingested key sits
      alongside the user's session — both are usable; selection is by
      priority.
    </p>

    <p>
      If the recipient has no session at all, the static
      <code>TinyCloudWeb.receiveShare(link, key?)</code> path is the right
      one. No <code>signIn</code>, no wallet, no IUserAuthorization.
      It decodes the link, sets up a one-shot <code>ServiceSession</code>
      from the bundle, registers the delegation with the host's
      <code>/delegate</code> endpoint, and fetches the requested key.
      It's a single function call, fully static.
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="padding: 14px 16px; margin: 16px 0; border-color: var(--accent);">
      <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">WASM init quirk</div>
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 14px;">
        <code>TinyCloudWeb.receiveShare</code> is a <em>static</em> method,
        which means there's no constructor doing WASM bootstrap. It calls
        <code>WasmInitializer.ensureInitialized()</code> at the top of the
        function — necessary because <code>decodeShareLink</code> uses the
        WASM bindings to validate the embedded delegation. If you've
        never instantiated <code>TinyCloudWeb</code> in this page, this is
        the line that triggers the wasm fetch.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>threat model — what a malicious share can do</h2>

    <div class="row gap-16" style="margin: 16px 0;">
      <div class="card tinted" style="flex:1; padding: 14px 16px;">
        <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">a malicious recipient</div>
        <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 20px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6;">
          <li>can do everything the delegation says they can — get, put, list, whatever was in <code>actions</code>.</li>
          <li>can sub-delegate further if <code>disableSubDelegation</code> wasn't set.</li>
          <li>can <em>not</em> escalate past the bundle's path/actions/expiry — the node enforces the same subset check on every invocation.</li>
          <li>can leak the bundle. anyone holding the link is the recipient. treat shares like bearer tokens.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card tinted" style="flex:1; padding: 14px 16px;">
        <div class="label" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">a malicious issuer</div>
        <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 20px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6;">
          <li>can only delegate from what they already hold. the chain they're sub-delegating from must subset-cover the share.</li>
          <li>can revoke at any time — <code>revokeDelegation(cid)</code> on the node-sdk; the share's <code>isRevoked</code> check fails fast on receive.</li>
          <li>cannot retroactively widen scope. issuing a new share doesn't change an old one.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>where the bundle lives in code</h2>

    <div class="row gap-16" style="margin: 16px 0;">
      <a href={`${base}/pkg/sdk-core/`} class="card" style="flex:1; padding: 14px 16px; text-decoration: none; color: var(--ink);">
        <div class="label">implementation</div>
        <div class="mono" style="margin: 4px 0; font-size: 13px;">{sdkCore.npm}</div>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 13px;">
          <code>SharingService</code> + <code>SharingService.schema</code>.
          {sdkCore.modules} modules · {sdkCore.loc.toLocaleString()} loc.
          Owns encoding, decoding, expiry &amp; revocation checks, and the
          ingestion-into-registry handoff.
        </p>
      </a>
      <a href={`${base}/pkg/web-sdk/`} class="card" style="flex:1; padding: 14px 16px; text-decoration: none; color: var(--ink);">
        <div class="label">browser surface</div>
        <div class="mono" style="margin: 4px 0; font-size: 13px;">{webSdk.npm}</div>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 13px;">
          <code>TinyCloudWeb.receiveShare</code> static method. Decodes,
          fetches, returns. {webSdk.modules} modules · {webSdk.loc.toLocaleString()} loc.
        </p>
      </a>
      <a href={`${base}/pkg/node-sdk/`} class="card" style="flex:1; padding: 14px 16px; text-decoration: none; color: var(--ink);">
        <div class="label">server surface</div>
        <div class="mono" style="margin: 4px 0; font-size: 13px;">{nodeSdk.npm}</div>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 13px;">
          <code>delegate</code> &amp; <code>revokeDelegation</code> for
          authoring; the same SharingService underneath.
          {nodeSdk.modules} modules · {nodeSdk.loc.toLocaleString()} loc.
        </p>
      </a>
    </div>

    <h3>data this chapter reads</h3>
    <ul class="col gap-4">
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/inventory.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/sdk-core.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/web-sdk.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/node-sdk.json</li>
      <li class="mono">/atlas/data/pkg/sdk-services.json</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>where to read next</h3>
    <p>
      Chapter <a class="pkg-link" href={`${base}/07/`}>07</a> turns the
      camera the other way: how the SDK and the node agree they're
      speaking the same protocol before any of these capabilities flow.
    </p>
  </article>
</Atlas>
